# Git + GitHub + VS Code (PBIP) — Practical Step-by-Step Cheat Sheet
This is a copy-pasteable guide you can keep in a repo (README.md). 
It covers: connecting VS Code to GitHub, pushing existing repos, pushing all branches, daily workflow, cloning, switching repos, fixing remotes, deleting branches, and common errors.

---

## 0) Vocabulary (so commands make sense)
* **repo**: the project folder containing a `.git` directory.
* **remote**: a saved “nickname” for a Git server URL (GitHub). Most common remote name: `origin`.
* **branch**: a line of work (e.g., `main`, `feature/new-visuals`).
* **upstream (tracking branch)**: the remote branch your local branch is linked to (so `git push`/`git pull` know where to go).

---

## 1) Connect GitHub to VS Code
### 1.1 Install GitHub extension (if you don’t see GitHub sign-in)

In VS Code:
* Extensions → search **GitHub Pull Requests and Issues** → Install
* Restart VS Code

### 1.2 Sign in to GitHub from VS Code
* Bottom-left **Accounts** icon → **Sign in with GitHub**
  Or:
* `Ctrl + Shift + P` → `GitHub: Sign in`

### 1.3 Confirm Git is installed
In VS Code terminal:

```bash
git --version
```

### 1.4 Set your Git identity (one-time)
```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@email.com"
```

---

## 2) Create a GitHub repo (website method)
Recommended for clean first push:

* GitHub → New repo
* Choose name + visibility
* IMPORTANT: Do **not** add README / .gitignore / license (keep remote empty)
Copy the HTTPS URL.

---

## 3) Push an EXISTING local repo (with history, branches, commits)
You already have `.git` locally and commits/branches exist.

### 3.1 Add the remote
```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/USER/REPO.git
```

Verify:
```bash
git remote -v
```

### 3.2 Push your main branch (or master)
If your main branch is `main`:

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

If it’s `master`:
```bash
git push -u origin master
```

### 3.3 Push ALL local branches to GitHub (everything)
```bash
git push -u origin --all
```

### 3.4 Push tags (if you use them)
```bash
git push --tags
```

---

## 4) Start a NEW repo locally, then push to GitHub
From inside your project folder:
### 4.1 Initialize + first commit

```bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

### 4.2 Add remote + push
```bash
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/USER/REPO.git
git push -u origin main
```

---

## 5) Daily workflow (most common loop)
### 5.1 Get latest changes before working

```bash
git pull
```

### 5.2 Stage changes

Stage everything:
```bash
git add .
```

Stage specific file(s):
```bash
git add path/to/file
```

### 5.3 Commit
```bash
git commit -m "Model Update: add Customer table and relationships"
```

### 5.4 Push
```bash
git push
```

---

## 6) New branch workflow (feature branch)

### 6.1 Create + switch to a new branch

```bash
git checkout -b model/add-new-table
```

### 6.2 First push of a new branch (sets upstream)
```bash
git push -u origin model/add-new-table
```

After you do that once, future pushes are just:
```bash
git push
```

---

## 7) Clone vs Pull (super important)
### 7.1 Clone (first time on a machine)
Clone creates a NEW local folder and sets remote automatically:

```bash
cd C:\Work
git clone https://github.com/USER/REPO.git
```

After cloning, you do NOT need `git remote add`. It’s already set.

### 7.2 Pull (updates an existing local repo)

Inside an already-cloned repo:

```bash
git pull
```

---

## 8) Switch to another repo in VS Code

A repo is just a folder with `.git`.

* VS Code → File → **Open Folder…** → choose the other repo folder
  or
* Close current folder → open another folder

In terminal, switching repos = changing directories:
```bash
cd path/to/other-repo
```

---

## 9) Remote cleanup and fixing “origin already exists”
### 9.1 See remotes

```bash
git remote -v
```

### 9.2 Remove a remote (example: remove broken origin)
```bash
git remote remove origin
```

### 9.3 Rename a remote (example: rename `repo` to `origin`)
```bash
git remote rename repo origin
```

### 9.4 Change the URL of origin (if origin exists but points to wrong place)
```bash
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/USER/NEWREPO.git
```

---

## 10) Windows error: “Deletion of directory … failed. Should I try again?”
This usually happens because Windows has files locked (VS Code, Power BI Desktop, antivirus).

Fix order:

1. Close VS Code fully
2. Close Power BI Desktop
3. Try again:

```bash
git remote remove origin
```

If still locked: restart the computer, then rerun the command.

---

## 11) Deleting branches (GitHub vs local)

### 11.1 If you delete a branch on GitHub

Local branch still exists. It may show “gone”:

```bash
git branch -vv
```

If you want to delete it locally too:

```bash
git branch -d branch-name
```

Force delete (only if you understand you’re discarding local work):

```bash
git branch -D branch-name
```

### 11.2 Delete remote branch from local terminal

```bash
git push origin --delete branch-name
```

---

## 12) “I pushed main but want EVERYTHING”

Push all local branches:

```bash
git push -u origin --all
```

Push tags too:

```bash
git push --tags
```

---

## 13) Useful checks (quick diagnostics)

Show current branch:

```bash
git branch
```

Show what changed:

```bash
git status
```

Show remotes:

```bash
git remote -v
```

Show upstream tracking status:

```bash
git branch -vv
```

---

## 14) Practical team rules (simple + safe)

* Work in feature branches for real changes.
* Pull before starting work.
* Commit messages should be clear and consistent:

  * `Model Update: ...`
  * `Visual Update: ...`
* First push for a new branch requires upstream:

  * `git push -u origin branch-name`
* After that, normal:

  * `git push`

---

## 15) PBIP note (keep repo clean)

PBIP is Git-friendly because it’s mostly text artifacts. Still:
* Avoid committing caches/temp folders.
* Keep a `.gitignore` appropriate for your environment.

---



If something breaks, run these three first:

```bash
git status
git branch -vv
git remote -v
```

They reveal 90% of issues immediately.

